---
import Callout from "@luciodale/docs-ui-kit/components/Callout.astro";
import CodeBlock from "@luciodale/docs-ui-kit/components/CodeBlock.astro";
import Comparison from "@luciodale/docs-ui-kit/components/Comparison.astro";
import ContentSection from "@luciodale/docs-ui-kit/components/ContentSection.astro";
import InlineCode from "@luciodale/docs-ui-kit/components/InlineCode.astro";
import DocsPage from "../../layouts/DocsPage.astro";
import { href } from "../../lib/link";

export const prerender = true;
---

<DocsPage
	title="react-searchable-dropdown vs Downshift"
	description="How react-searchable-dropdown compares to Downshift. Honest trade-offs on headless flexibility, accessibility, virtualization, and batteries included for React combobox builds."
>
	<ContentSection label="The choice">
		<p class="text-white/60 mb-4 leading-relaxed">
			Downshift (by Kent C. Dodds and Alex Reardon) is the headless
			reference for combobox and select in React. It ships nothing but
			accessibility primitives, keyboard handling, and state. No markup,
			no styling, no virtualization. Every pixel you see is yours to
			build, and the library keeps the A11y contract watertight along
			the way.
		</p>
		<p class="text-white/60 leading-relaxed">
			react-searchable-dropdown is the opposite axis: a component with
			opinions. Virtualized rendering, fuzzy search, portal positioning,
			chips, and grouping are defaults, not exercises. You trade
			Downshift's flexibility for a faster path from npm install to
			working dropdown.
		</p>
	</ContentSection>

	<ContentSection label="Where each one sits">
		<p class="text-white/60 mb-4 leading-relaxed">
			Downshift sits at the "do less" end of the spectrum on purpose.
			It's a set of hooks (<InlineCode>useSelect</InlineCode>,
			<InlineCode>useCombobox</InlineCode>,
			<InlineCode>useMultipleSelection</InlineCode>) that hand you the
			state, the event handlers, and the correct ARIA attributes. Every
			render decision is yours.
		</p>
		<p class="text-white/60 leading-relaxed">
			react-searchable-dropdown sits further toward "batteries included."
			It still gives you styling hooks and type safety, but you don't
			write the list, the input, the chip row, or the keyboard handler
			yourself. If you need to ship a combobox today, that matters.
		</p>
	</ContentSection>

	<ContentSection label="Feature by feature">
		<Comparison
			columns={[
				{
					name: "@luciodale/react-searchable-dropdown",
					href: "https://www.npmjs.com/package/@luciodale/react-searchable-dropdown",
					tagline: "Component, batteries included",
					highlight: true,
				},
				{
					name: "downshift",
					href: "https://www.npmjs.com/package/downshift",
					tagline: "Headless hooks, bring your own UI",
				},
			]}
			rows={[
				{
					feature: "Ships the markup",
					description:
						"Input, list, chips rendered for you out of the box.",
					values: ["yes", "no"],
				},
				{
					feature: "Virtualized option list",
					description:
						"Handles 100k+ options without jank.",
					values: ["yes", "no"],
				},
				{
					feature: "Fuzzy search built in",
					description:
						"Typo tolerant, with highlight.",
					values: ["yes", "no"],
				},
				{
					feature: "Portal positioning",
					description:
						"Floating UI integration, handles modals and scroll containers.",
					values: ["yes", "no"],
				},
				{
					feature: "Multi select chips",
					description:
						"Removable chips, clear all, backspace to remove last.",
					values: ["yes", { text: "Via useMultipleSelection hook" }],
				},
				{
					feature: "Grouped options",
					values: ["yes", { text: "Build your own" }],
				},
				{
					feature: "ARIA combobox pattern",
					description:
						"Full keyboard support, focus management, screen reader announcements.",
					values: ["yes", "yes"],
				},
				{
					feature: "Headless / full render control",
					description:
						"Every element rendered by you.",
					values: [
						{ text: "className slots + CSS vars" },
						"yes",
					],
				},
				{
					feature: "Styling freedom",
					values: [
						{ text: "Slots + CSS vars" },
						{ text: "Unlimited (you render it)" },
					],
				},
				{
					feature: "Production track record",
					values: [
						{ text: "Young" },
						{ text: "10+ years, industry reference" },
					],
				},
				{
					feature: "Bundle size (min+gz, core)",
					values: [{ text: "~15 kB" }, { text: "~4 kB (no UI)" }],
				},
				{
					feature: "Time to first working combobox",
					values: [
						{ text: "Minutes" },
						{ text: "Hours (you build the UI)" },
					],
				},
			]}
			caption="Feature comparison between react-searchable-dropdown and downshift"
		/>
	</ContentSection>

	<ContentSection label="The headless trade off">
		<p class="text-white/60 mb-4 leading-relaxed">
			Downshift is the correct answer when your design system has
			specific requirements that don't fit any existing component. The
			library guarantees accessibility, you guarantee everything else.
			That's powerful, and it's also a commitment: you own rendering,
			keyboard edge cases, filtering, virtualization, positioning, and
			every future behavior.
		</p>
		<CodeBlock
			code={`// Downshift: you render every element
const { getToggleButtonProps, getMenuProps, getItemProps, isOpen } = useSelect({
  items: options,
});

return (
  <div>
    <button {...getToggleButtonProps()}>{selectedItem?.label ?? "Pick"}</button>
    <ul {...getMenuProps()} hidden={!isOpen}>
      {isOpen && options.map((opt, i) => (
        <li key={opt.value} {...getItemProps({ item: opt, index: i })}>
          {opt.label}
        </li>
      ))}
    </ul>
  </div>
);`}
			language="tsx"
			filename="downshift.tsx"
		/>
		<p class="text-white/60 mb-4 mt-4 leading-relaxed">
			react-searchable-dropdown picks sensible defaults and lets you
			override the pieces you care about via className slots and CSS
			variables.
		</p>
		<CodeBlock
			code={`<SearchableDropdown
  options={cities}
  value={city}
  setValue={setCity}
  placeholder="Pick a city"
/>`}
			language="tsx"
			filename="dropdown.tsx"
		/>
	</ContentSection>

	<ContentSection label="When to pick Downshift">
		<Callout type="info" title="Pick it when">
			Your design system has bespoke requirements: custom list virtuals,
			non standard input patterns, combobox behavior that no component
			lib covers. You want the battle tested A11y primitives and to
			render everything yourself. Your team is comfortable shipping
			keyboard + ARIA edge cases.
		</Callout>
	</ContentSection>

	<ContentSection label="When to pick react-searchable-dropdown">
		<Callout type="tip" title="Pick it when">
			You want virtualization, fuzzy search, and portal positioning on
			day one. A working, accessible dropdown that looks reasonable by
			default is more valuable than total render control. You'd rather
			theme with className slots than build the DOM yourself.
		</Callout>
	</ContentSection>

	<ContentSection label="Next steps">
		<ul class="space-y-2 text-white/60">
			<li>
				<a href={href("/docs/vs-react-select")} class="text-accent hover:underline">vs react-select</a> — if you're comparing to the component-heavy camp
			</li>
			<li>
				<a href={href("/docs/getting-started")} class="text-accent hover:underline">Getting started</a> — install and drop it in
			</li>
			<li>
				<a href={href("/docs/styling")} class="text-accent hover:underline">Styling</a> — className slots and CSS variables
			</li>
		</ul>
	</ContentSection>
</DocsPage>
